{"source_key":"sha256-030eed7c2b37e7a052500d0b6a51d640","record_index":260,"record_hash":"sha256:98b9a1027627e4002a4949b9119802d2d9891f12e79aa55971efe51dd3a2c890","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:04:57.621Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"Privacy review: the doc is close, but one thing is still muddy enough to bite us.\\n\\n**Highest-Signal Risks**\\n\\n1. **Publication boundary is internally conflicted.**  \\n   The doc says URL replacement may generate a page from public metadata, but also says “no automatic public publishing just because capture succeeded.” Those can’t both be true unless we define the v1 rule.  \\n   See [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:162>) and [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:516>).\\n\\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   For public v1, Agent Trail treats a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` as already published metadata. On-demand URL replacement does not grant access to private data; it only renders a review page from metadata that is fetchable without credentials.\\n   ```\\n\\n   Or, if that is too permissive:\\n   ```md\\n   Publicly fetchable metadata is necessary but not sufficient. A trail is only renderable when the metadata contains an explicit publish marker for that PR/review target.\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **“No extra public redaction” makes `but-agentlog`’s guarantees load-bearing.**  \\n   That’s fine, but the doc should say this sharply. Right now it lists things that “should not be exposed” while also saying Forge won’t add another redaction layer.  \\n   See [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:69>) and [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:478>).\\n\\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   Because v1 has no Forge-specific public redaction pass, Forge must only render records returned by a `but-agentlog` public/read projection whose redaction guarantees are explicit. Forge must not read or render raw internal records directly.\\n   ```\\n\\n3. **Branch fallback can accidentally surface unrelated sessions.**  \\n   Branch names are weak identifiers. If review-target lookup fails, branch-only hits should not feel equivalent. The doc says this, but I’d make the display rule stronger.  \\n   See [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:140>).\\n\\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   Branch-only matches are possible evidence, not selected proof. In v1 they should be visually separated from review-target matches and labeled as weaker matches. Raw record drill-down for branch-only matches should require an explicit expand action.\\n   ```\\n\\n4. **Public on-demand fetching is a DoS surface.**  \\n   Anyone can hand the service a public GitHub PR URL. The doc mentions bare caches and locks, but should also call out fetch/resource limits.  \\n   See [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:297>).\\n\\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   V1 should only accept recognized GitHub PR URL shapes, never arbitrary git URLs. Repository initialization and metadata fetches need timeouts, size limits, per-repo locking, rate limits, and cleanup. The server must not run hooks, recurse submodules, fetch LFS, or execute repository content.\\n   ```\\n\\n5. **Forks need an explicit hard stop.**  \\n   The doc says forks are unsupported, but branch fallback could still accidentally use a head branch name from a fork. Make the behavior concrete.  \\n   See [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:68>).\\n\\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   If a PR head repository is different from the base repository, v1 should not use branch fallback. It should return an unsupported-fork state unless review-target metadata is available from the base repository metadata ref.\\n   ```\\n\\n6. **Snapshots need indexing/cache posture.**  \\n   Even for public repos, Agent Trail makes obscure metadata easy to browse. That is amplification. I’d add `noindex` for v1 unless the goal is public SEO.  \\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   Public v1 snapshots should be treated as public-but-not-promoted: stable enough to share, but served with `noindex` until the publication model is mature.\\n   ```\\n\\n**Must-Ask Before Building**\\n\\n1. Is a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` enough consent to render Agent Trail publicly, or do we need an explicit publish marker per PR/review?\\n\\n2. For branch-only matches, are we okay showing them automatically as weaker evidence, or should v1 only show review-target matches unless the user explicitly asks for broader matches?\\n\\nEverything else can wait. These two shape the first implementation in ways that are annoying to reverse later.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:04:57.621Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}